U.S. Gulf Crude Premiums Strengthen as Brent-WTI Spread Widens

-- B y   A a r o n   C l a r k
-- 
2011-07-22T17:52:50Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-22/u-s-gulf-crude-premiums-strengthen-as-brent-wti-spread-widens.html
Crude oil premiums in the U.S. Gulf
gained as the spread widened between the U.S. benchmark West
Texas Intermediate and Brent.  The gap increased 22 cents to $18.60 a barrel as of 1:33
p.m. in  New York . The spread settled at a record high of $22.63
a barrel July 14. When Brent gains versus WTI, it strengthens
the value of low-sulfur U.S. grades that compete with West
African oil priced against the European benchmark.  Light Louisiana Sweet’s premium rose 70 cents to $19.70 a
barrel over WTI as of 12:08 p.m. in New York, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg. Heavy Louisiana Sweet’s premium widened
$1.75 a barrel to $22.25 a barrel.  Among sour, or high-sulfur, grades, the premium for Mars
Blend lost 25 cents to $15.25 while Poseidon’s narrowed 20 cents
to $14.80 a barrel.  Southern Green Canyon’s premium was unchanged at $12.25 a
barrel over WTI. West Texas Sour’s discount widened 35 cents to
$1.10 below the benchmark. Thunder Horse’s premium gained $1.50
a barrel to $21.  The premium for Syncrude was unchanged at $10.70. Syncrude
is a light, low-sulfur synthetic oil derived from the tar sands
in  Alberta .  The discount for Western Canada Select was unchanged at
$18.75 a barrel.  To contact the reporter on this story:
